      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Housing Crisis</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael Turk letter, comments on Sec Andrew M Cuomo's Aug 22 article on Vice Pres Al Gore's agenda, saying affordable housing needs to be addressed in any populist program for new century</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is paradoxical that Andrew M. Cuomo, the federal housing secretary, cites as central to Al Gore's campaign the need to make health care and college education affordable to working families but does not mention housing (news article, Aug. 22).</p>
        <p>In 1990, roughly one in four households spent at least 30 percent of their income on housing. Yet since then, as the Department of Housing and Urban Development reported only last fall, there has been a ''widening'' of the affordability gap for millions of the country's poorest households.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is paradoxical that Andrew M. Cuomo, the federal housing secretary, cites as central to Al Gore's campaign the need to make health care and college education affordable to working families but does not mention housing (news article, Aug. 22).</p>
        <p>In 1990, roughly one in four households spent at least 30 percent of their income on housing. Yet since then, as the Department of Housing and Urban Development reported only last fall, there has been a ''widening'' of the affordability gap for millions of the country's poorest households.</p>
        <p>Like access to affordable health care, the lack or limited availability of affordable housing contributes to the undertow beneath today's wave of prosperity for a sizable portion of the population. It needs to be addressed in any populist program for the new century.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL TURK  Cambridge, Mass., Aug. 23, 2000</p>
      </block>
